SIMPLE: obscene
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Obscene
<hw>Ob*scene"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>obscenus</ets>, <ets>obscaenus</ets>, <ets>obscoenus</ets>, ill
looking, filthy, obscene: cf. F. <ets>obsc⟦eacute⟧ne</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Offensive to chastity or modesty; expressing or
presenting to the mind or view something which delicacy, purity, and
decency forbid to be exposed; impure; <as>as, <ex>obscene</ex> language;
<ex>obscene</ex> pictures.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Words that were once chaste, by frequent use grew
<qex>obscene</qex> and uncleanly.</q> <rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Foul; filthy; disgusting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A girdle foul with grease binds his <qex>obscene</qex> attire.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden (Aeneid, vi. 417).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Inauspicious; ill-omened.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<mark>[A Latinism]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At the cheerful light,⟦br⟧
The groaning ghosts and birds <qex>obscene</qex> take flight.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Impure; immodest; indecent; unchaste;
lewd.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Ob*scene"ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Ob*scene"ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Obscenity</ent>⟦br⟧
